[[Image:Map of Slovenian dialects.svg|thumb|400px|Map of regional groups of [[Slovene dialects]] {{legend|#aa0000|Carinthian}}]]
The '''Carinthian dialect group''' (''koroška narečna skupina'', ''koroščina''<ref name="Logar">Logar, Tine. 1996. ''Dialektološke in jezikovnozgodovinske razprave''. Ljubljana: SAZU.</ref>{{rp|71}}) is a group of closely related dialects of [[Slovene language|Slovene]]. The Carinthian dialects are spoken by [[Carinthian Slovenes]] in Austria, in [[Slovenian Carinthia]], and in the northwestern parts of [[Slovenian Styria]] along the upper [[Drava]] Valley, in the westernmost areas of [[Upper Carniola]] on the border with [[Italy]], and in some villages in the [[Province of Udine]] in Italy.
==Phonological and morphological characteristics== Among other features, this group is characterized by late denasalization of *''ę'' and *''ǫ'', a close reflex of long [[yat]] and open reflex of short [[yat]], lengthening of old acute syllables and short neo-acute syllables, and an ''e''-like reflex of the long semivowel and ''ə''-like reflex of the short semivowel.<ref>Toporišič, Jože. 1992. ''Enciklopedija slovenskega jezika''. Ljubljana: Cankarjeva založba, p. 88.</ref>
==Individual dialects and subdialects== * [[North Pohorje–Remšnik dialect]] (''severnopohorsko-remšniško narečje'') * [[Mežica dialect]] (''mežiško narečje'', ''mežiščina''<ref name="Rigler">Rigler, Jakob. 1986. ''Razprave o slovenskem jeziku''. Ljubljana: Slovenska matica.</ref>{{rp|155}}) * [[Jaun Valley dialect]] (''podjunsko narečje'', ''podjunščina''<ref name="Rigler"/>{{rp|177}}) (Austria) * [[Ebriach dialect]] (''obirsko narečje'', ''obirščina''<ref name="Logar"/>{{rp|23}}) (Austria) * [[Rosen Valley dialect]] (''rožansko narečje'', ''rožanščina''<ref name="Logar"/>{{rp|20}}) (Austria) * [[Gail Valley dialect]] (''ziljsko narečje'', ''ziljščina''<ref name="Logar"/>{{rp|20}}) (Austria, Italy) ** [[Kranjska Gora subdialect]] (''kranjskogorski govor'')
