[[Category:Hindi languages]] [[Category:Indo-Aryan languages]] [[Category:Hindi]] {{language-stub}}

'''Skill-based theories of second-language acquisition''' are [[theories of second-language acquisition|theories]] of [[second-language acquisition]] based on models of [[skill acquisition]] in [[cognitive psychology]]. These theories conceive of second-language acquisition as being learned in the same way as any other skill, such as learning to drive a car or play the piano. That is, they see [[practice (learning method)|practice]] as the key ingredient of language acquisition. The most well-known of these theories is based on [[John Robert Anderson (psychologist)|John Anderson]]'s [[adaptive control of thought]] model.<ref name="VanPatten2010skill">{{Harvnb|VanPatten|Benati|2010|pp=149–150}}, "Skill/s".</ref>

== Adaptive control of thought ==
{{Main|ACT-R}}
The adaptive control of thought model assumes a distinction between [[declarative knowledge]], knowledge that is conscious and consists of facts,<ref name="Schmidt2010declarative">{{Harvnb|Richards|Schmidt|2009}}, "Declarative knowledge".</ref> and [[procedural knowledge]], knowledge of how an activity is done.<ref name="Schmidt2010procedural">{{Harvnb|Richards|Schmidt|2009}}, "Procedural knowledge".</ref><ref name="Schmidt2010ACT">{{Harvnb|Richards|Schmidt|2009}}, "Adaptive control of thought".</ref> In this model, skill acquisition is seen as a progression from declarative to procedural knowledge.<ref name="Schmidt2010ACT" /> Adaptive control of thought is a general model of cognition, and second-language acquisition is just one application of a wide area of research in cognitive psychology.<ref name="VanPatten2010ACT">{{Harvnb|VanPatten|Benati|2010|p=62}}, "Adaptive Control of Thought model".</ref> Second-language acquisition is seen as a progression through three stages, declarative, procedural, and autonomous.<ref name="VanPatten2010ACT" />

