{{Infobox language |name=ǃGãǃne |altname= |region=South Africa |extinct=early 20th century |familycolor=Khoisan |fam1=[[Tuu languages|Tuu]] |fam2=ǃKwi |fam3= |iso3=none |iso3comment=included in {{ethnolink|kqu}}<ref>''Ethnologue'' erroneously includes !Gã!ne in Seroa, but the two languages have only one known word in common.</ref> |glotto=gang1269 |glottorefname=!Gã!nge }}
'''ǃGãǃne''' (!Gã!nge) is an [[List of extinct languages|extinct]] language of the [[Tuu languages|ǃKwi]] family, once spoken near [[Tsolo]] and in [[Umtata]] District in South Africa, south of Lesotho. The only material on the language is 140 words collected from two semi-speakers (rememberers) in 1931.<ref name=Traill>Anthony Traill, "The Khoisan Languages of South Africa", in Rajend Mesthrie, ed., 1995, ''Language and Social History: Studies in South African Sociolinguistics''</ref>
Like [[ǁXegwi language|ǁXegwi]], ǃGãǃne is considered an "outlier" among the !Kwi languages by Güldemann (2005, 2011). ''[[Ethnologue]]'' and ''Glottolog'' count it as a dialect of [[Seroa language|Seroa]],<ref>{{e18|kqu|Seroa}}</ref> though the two have no demonstrable connection apart from being in the !Kwi family.<ref name="Traill" />
